=====Argentina=====
"In 2008, in the Argentine province of Santiago del Estero, seven babies died while taking part in trials for an experimental vaccine made by GlaxoSmithKline to prevent pneumonia and related diseases." <ref>{{cite news |title=The Other South American Drug War |date=10/10/2011 |last=Hearn |first=Kelly |newspaper=The Nation}}</ref>

=====Israel=====
In Israel, a former worker of [[Negev Nuclear Research Center]] filed lawsuit, claiming that employees of the Center were given drinks with [[uranium]] without medical supervision and without obtaining written consent.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/1107980.html |title=Ex-staffer at Dimona nuclear reactor says made to drink uranium |date=2009-01-01 |accessdate=2009-08-19 |publisher=Haaretz.com}}</ref>

=====India=====
The prevalence of pharmaceutical drug trials are drastically increasing in India. AstraZeneca has opened a drug-testing facility in Bangalore and Pfizer has done the same in Bombay.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://ehis.ebscohost.com/eds/delivery?sid=cc26ec2d-b2c4=4c66-9667-6162863de2f3%40se.html | title= Poor, sick, desperate. What more could Big Pharma ask in Indian drug Trials? | first=Anjana | last=Ahuja |newspaper=[[The Times]] | date= 05/08/2006}}</ref> In 2005, the law that was put in place a year prior that required for drugs to receive safety approval in their home countries before being tested in India was repealed.

